(Sunford Heat Action Plan) Tj
T*
(Source ID: sunford_heat_action) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(This fictional city brief was created for teaching RAG retrieval and evaluation.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Sunford is a fictional inland city where summer nights are getting warmer. The heat action) Tj
T*
(plan focuses on the urban heat island in Oak Market, South Loop, and the eastern warehouse) Tj
T*
(district. Local sensors show that paved streets can stay 6 C warmer than parks after sunset.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The city defines a heat alert as two forecast days above 32 C or one night above 24 C. When an) Tj
T*
(alert is active, libraries, sports halls, and two school cafeterias become cooling centers.) Tj
T*
(The plan prioritizes elderly residents, people without air conditioning, outdoor workers, and) Tj
T*
(families with infants.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Sunford will plant 12,000 shade trees over five years. The first planting corridors are bus) Tj
T*
(stops, school walking routes, and streets with high elderly populations. Tree maintenance is) Tj
T*
(funded for the full period because previous planting efforts failed when young trees were not) Tj
T*
(watered during drought weeks.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Public housing blocks in Oak Market will receive cool roof coatings and reflective courtyard) Tj
T*
(surfaces. The plan treats these as heat mitigation measures because they lower neighborhood) Tj
T*
(temperatures before an emergency happens. Cooling centers and outreach vans are heat response) Tj
T*
(measures because they help people during an active heat event.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Outdoor worker outreach is run with unions and large employers. During red alerts,) Tj
T*
(construction sites must shift heavy work away from early afternoon where possible. Outreach) Tj
T*
(vans distribute water, shade tents, and heat illness cards in multiple languages. The cards) Tj
T*
(describe dizziness, confusion, and stopped sweating as warning signs.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The communication system combines text messages, radio announcements, and door-to-door checks.) Tj
T*
(A heat-health SMS alert is sent when the forecast threshold is crossed. Community volunteers) Tj
T*
(then contact registered high-risk residents. The plan says digital alerts alone are not enough) Tj
T*
(because the residents most at risk may not check phones regularly.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(The evaluation target is a 30 percent reduction in heat-related ambulance calls from Oak) Tj
T*
(Market within four summers. The plan also tracks night temperature, cooling center visits, and) Tj
T*
(tree survival. Sunford expects slow improvement because shade trees need time to mature.) Tj
T*
() Tj
